Aburizal Bakrie, the Coordinating Minister for Social Welfare, faced scrutiny over his handling of an environmental disaster caused by a mud volcano in Indonesia.
Bakrie downplayed the toxicity of the mud and shifted blame to an earthquake, distancing his family's company, Lapindo Brantas Inc., from the incident.
The mud flow, ongoing since May, has displaced thousands and led to fatalities.
Efforts to contain the disaster include dropping concrete balls into the volcano, rerouting infrastructure, and legal action against responsible parties, including President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono.
